<article class="vd">

  <!-- MASTHEAD -->
  <div class="vd-masthead">
    <div class="vd-wrap-wide vd-masthead-inner">
      <div class="vd-pub">Velvy <span class="sep">·</span> Editorial</div>
      <div class="vd-pub-tag"><span class="red">●</span> Prevention Series <span class="sep" style="color:#2A251D;">·</span> Issue 03</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- HERO -->
  <header class="vd-hero">
    <div class="vd-wrap">
      <div class="vd-cat"><span class="num">01</span> Investigation · Road safety</div>
      <h1 class="vd-h1">Re-introducing the object on the back of your <em>head.</em></h1>
      <p class="vd-lede">On a hard brake, it doesn't bend. It breaks. And shards don't ask where they land. <strong>The plastic claw clip has been sitting between your skull and your headrest for years</strong> — and nobody, until now, has bothered to ask whether that's a good idea.</p>

      <div class="vd-author">
        <img src="{{ img_avatar }}" alt="Léa Marchand, Contributing Editor">
        <div class="vd-author-meta">
          <div class="vd-author-name">By Léa Marchand</div>
          <div class="vd-author-role">Contributing Editor · Lifestyle</div>
          <div class="vd-author-meta-sub">Published May 14, 2026<span class="dot">·</span>6 min read<span class="dot">·</span>Updated May 17</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="vd-hero-img">
      <div class="vd-wrap">
        <img src="{{ img_hero }}" alt="Aftermath of a low-speed collision: a plastic claw clip has shattered, with shards entangled in a woman's hair against the car headrest" loading="eager">
        <div class="vd-figcap"><b>Documented</b>Low-speed rear-end impact. The standard plastic claw clip fractured against the headrest, depositing shards through the wearer's hair and onto her neck. A small linear abrasion is visible. Composite reconstructed from incident-reporting data.</div>
