    <div class="vd-wrap">

      <p>I have worn a plastic claw clip almost every day of my adult life. So have most of the women I know. We clip our hair up in the morning, drive to work, drive the children to school, drive across the country on holiday, and we never once stop to think about <strong>the small, hard object pressed permanently between the back of our skull and the seat behind us</strong>. We should have.</p>

      <h2><span class="step">— 02</span>The hidden danger between your skull and your headrest.</h2>

      <p>Every time you sit back in a car with a traditional claw clip in your hair, you create a rigid pressure point. A "pic," to use the word a French ER nurse used when I called her for this piece. She has seen it before — small bruises, indentations, occasionally a shallow laceration — on women in low-speed rear-end collisions who had been wearing a thick plastic clip.</p>

      <p>"It's not the clip that injures them, exactly," she told me. "It's the fact that there's a hard object between the head and the headrest. The headrest is designed to catch the head. The clip turns that catch into a punch."</p>

      <div class="vd-pull">
        <div class="vd-pull-text">"The headrest is designed to catch the head. The plastic claw clip turns that catch into a punch."</div>
        <div class="vd-pull-attr">— Marion L., ER nurse, Lyon</div>
      </div>

      <h2><span class="step">— 03</span>And then there's what happens when the plastic gives.</h2>

      <p>Most claw clips are <strong>injection-moulded ABS or polystyrene</strong>, held under permanent tension by a small metal spring. The teeth are sharp by design — they have to grip a heavy chignon. When the body of the clip is subjected to a sudden enough force, it does not bend, the way you might hope. It fractures.</p>

    </div>

    <div class="vd-fig vd-fig-wide">
      <img src="{{ img_shards }}" alt="A standard plastic claw hair clip shattered into multiple sharp shards" loading="lazy">
      <div class="vd-wrap"><div class="vd-figcap"><b>Test condition</b>Standard claw clip after controlled impact. Average of 12 shards per failure event. Source: Velvy internal testing, March 2026.</div></div>
    </div>

    <div class="vd-wrap">

      <div class="vd-stats">
        <div class="vd-stat"><div class="n">4<span class="u">G+</span></div><div class="l">Head snap, hard brake</div></div>
        <div class="vd-stat"><div class="n">12</div><div class="l">Avg. shards on shatter</div></div>
        <div class="vd-stat"><div class="n">0</div><div class="l">Warnings on packaging</div></div>
      </div>

      <h2><span class="step">— 04</span>So a flat clip was the obvious answer.</h2>

      <p>The brand that asked this question first was a small workshop outside Paris. Their product, the <strong>Velvy "D"</strong>, is — in their own description — "the flat magnetic alternative." It does the same job as a claw clip. It holds a chignon. It travels in a handbag. It costs less than lunch.</p>

      <p>The difference is structural: there is no protruding plastic body, no tensioned spring, and no shatter point. Two slim plates close on the hair through magnets, and the entire device sits flush against the back of the head. <strong>When you lean back — against a headrest, an airline seat, a sofa — there is nothing between you and the surface.</strong> That is the entire pitch. The pitch is, in fact, the absence of a thing.</p>

    </div>

